I"Ì<h2 id="1-install-image-magick-in-ubuntu">1. Install Image Magick in Ubuntu.</h2>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nb">sudo </span>apt <span class="nb">install </span>gcc imagemagick
</code></pre></div></div>

<h2 id="2-using-your-icon-design-create-the-source-files">2. Using your icon design create the source files.</h2>
<p>Remember that each size should be a square and you need to make sure to have all this sizes so any device can render it correctly, the files could be .png, .jpg or .bmp.</p>

<ul>
  <li>icon-512.png</li>
  <li>icon-256.png</li>
  <li>icon-128.png</li>
  <li>icon-64.png</li>
  <li>icon-32.png</li>
</ul>

<p>Be careful and save all of the icons in the same directory.</p>

<h2 id="3-use-image-magick-to-generate-the-favicon">3. Use Image Magick to generate the favicon.</h2>
<p>Move in to the icons directory on your terminal.</p>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nb">cd</span> /dir/to/my/icons/directory
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Then run the image magick command to create the favicon based on all of the given icons.</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>convert icon-32.png icon-64.png icon-128.png icon-256.png icon-512.png favicon.ico
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>And there you are, multi resolution favicon ready to go.</p>
